AFL Systems Architecture Board v1
Purpose

This document captures the high‑level architecture for Avatar Fight League (AFL). It defines the systems, modules and data flows required to build a modular, scalable robotics sports‑combat platform in Unreal. It sets clear ownership boundaries to prevent feature creep and ensures that all future modes (Assault, Laser Tag, Paintball) plug into a common combat and arena framework.

1. Core Modules and Responsibilities
Module	Responsibility
AFLCore	Base robot pawn, shared stats (health, structure, stamina, energy), team enums and tags.
AFLCombatCore	Shared combat vocabulary, hit routing, damage event interfaces, combat data assets.
AFLCombatMelee	Tackle, collision and knockback logic for impact‑based combat.
AFLCombatHitscan	Hitscan/beam weapons, trace confirmation and scoring for laser tag.
AFLCombatProjectile	Projectile spawning, travel, splat and paint logic for paintball.
AFLArena	Round manager, spawn zones, objective zones, overtime, win conditions, map‑level hazards.
AFLModeAssault	Assault Core ruleset (objective capture/pressure, denial, scoring).
AFLModeLaserTag	Laser Tag mode ruleset (hitscan scoring and respawn pacing).
AFLModePaintball	Paintball mode ruleset (projectile splat and zone pressure/elimination).
AFLMatchmaking	Queue creation, party/lobby management, session assignment, skill rating integration.
AFLEconomy	Soft currency (Coins), access Tickets, XP, reward calculation, anti‑abuse checks.
AFLProgression	XP tracking, mastery, seasonal progression, player performance bands.
AFLBroadcast	Spectator cameras, replay hooks, HUD overlays, broadcast events.
AFLAudio	Imported announcer/voice assets, event sound routing, robot voice triggers.
AFLUI	Menu flows, queue UI, HUD/telemetry panels, match summary screens.
AFLNet	Network/session scaffolding, replication helpers and online authority.
AFLTools	Development utilities, validation scripts, debug visualizers, automation hooks.
